15+ laws of  UI/UX design

1. Asethetic-usability effect
   ğŸ’ users often percevie aesthetically pleasing design as design that's more usable
2. Doherty threshold
  ğŸ’  Productivity soars when a computer and its users interact at a pace(<400ms) that ensures that neither has to wait on the other
3. Fitts' law
  ğŸ’ The time to acquire a target is a function of the distance to and size of the target.
4. Hick's law
  ğŸ’ the time it takes to make a decision increases with the number and complexity of choices
5. Jakob's law
  ğŸ’ users spend most of their time on other sites. This means that users prefer your site to work the same way as all the other sites they already know.
6. Law of common region
   ğŸ’ elements tend to be preceived into groups if they are sharing an area with a clearly defined boundary.
7. Law of pragnanz
   ğŸ’ people will perceive and interpret ambiguous or complex images as the simplest form possible, because it is the interpretation that requires the least cognitive effort of us.
8. Law of proximity
    ğŸ’ objects that are near or proximate to each other, tend to be grouped together.
9. Law of similarity
    ğŸ’ the human eye tends to perceive similar elements in a design as a complete picture, shape or group, even if those elements are separated.
10. Uniform connectedness
    ğŸ’ elements that are visually connected are perceived as more relate than elements with no connection
11. Miller's law 
    ğŸ’ the average person can only keep 7(plus or minus 2) items in their working memory.
12. Occam's Razor
     ğŸ’ among competing hyotheses that predict equally well, the one with the fewest assumptions should be selected.
13. Pareto Principle 
     ğŸ’ the pareto principle states that, for many events, roughly 80% of the effects come from 20% of the causes.
14. Parkinson's law
    ğŸ’  any task inflate until all of the available time is spent.
15. postel's law
     ğŸ’  Be liberal in what you accept, and conservative in what you send.
16. Serial position effect
    ğŸ’ users have a propensity to best remember the first and last items in a series.
17. Tesler's law 
    ğŸ’  tesler's law, also known as the law of conservation of complexity, states that for any system there is a certain amount of complexity which cannot be reduced.
18. Von Restorff Effect
    ğŸ’  The von restorff effect, also known as the isolation effect, predict that when multiple similar objects are present, the one that differ from the rest is most likely to be remembered.
19. Zeigarnik effect
   ğŸ’ people remember uncompleted or interrupted tasks better than completed tasks.




